ce:section.ce:para:
In the synthesis of multiple-color and afterglow emission CDs, DTSA with rich carbonyl groups and biphenyl ring was selected as the precursor and boric acid as the matrix (Fig. 1
                     ). The tunable color and time-dependent afterglow properties of CDs@BA were regulated by a facile thermal treatment, changing the synthesis temperature. The selected precursor with a symmetrical molecular structure was expected to feature the graphitized carbon core with additional oxygen-containing surface groups during the thermally induced carbonization process [9,43], thus generating and activating multiple PL centers in the CDs@BA samples. The presence of carboxyl and carbonyl groups is expected to promote the population of the triplet state (T1) by spin-orbit coupling and increase the radiation probability of phosphorescence via triplet state emission or DF via singlet emission after the reverse intersystem crossing from triplet state to singlet excited state (S1) [44,45]. BA served as both a crossing linking agent and host media to consolidate singlet/triplet excitons and enhance the PL properties. Fig. 2
                     (a) shows the variation trend of afterglow color within 1 s of the as-synthesized three CDs@BA samples at 180 °C, 200 °C, and 230 °C, labeled as CDs@BA1, CDs@BA2, and CDs@BA3, respectively. We can see that these CDs@BA demonstrate different prompt emission colors under the UV excitation, and particularly, the time-dependent afterglow luminescence changes in different color ranges. Specifically, when the UV excitation light was turned off, a slightly changing color of indigo-green afterglow over time was observed for CDs@BA1, suggesting an inefficient construction of multiple afterglow luminescence centers at this temperature. With increasing reaction temperatures, the increased oxidization would promote the generation of oxygen-containing surface groups associated with the red emission centers. Accordingly, the increased contributions from red emissive centers with different spectra, lifetimes, and relative proportions in the PL spectra result in their broadband and time-dependent afterglow properties for CDs@BA2 and CDs@BA3. Particularly, CDs@BA3 exhibits a significant dynamic afterglow color to the naked eye. Compared with the situation of CDs@BA2 evolved an afterglow color changing from yellow to green within 1 s, the tuning range of the afterglow color for CDs@BA3 covered a larger spectral region from red to green after ceasing the lamp excitation within the same time duration. These observations demonstrate the thermally induced effects on the afterglow properties of CDs@BA.
